click-skills — vendored company skills for the Click ecosystem
==============================================================

The skills under `skills/` in this plugin are a pinned, vendored snapshot of the
Zesh-One company skills repository:

    Source:  https://github.com/zeshone/zesh-one-skills
    Version: v2.7.0 (commit 57bbdf3)  — see UPSTREAM_VERSION

They are vendored (rather than fetched at install time) so that `click install`
is offline-safe and reproducible, and so the exact skill content shipped to
developers is reviewable in this repository.

Provenance and licensing
-------------------------
- Each `skills/<name>/SKILL.md` preserves the upstream `license:` field
  declared in its own YAML frontmatter (Apache-2.0 for the Zesh-One skills).
  That per-skill declaration is authoritative for each file; the root
  LICENSE (Apache-2.0) in this directory is provided to back those declarations
  for the collection as a whole.
- The upstream repository has no root LICENSE file of its own; the individual
  skills declare Apache-2.0. Vendoring here was authorized by the repository
  owner on that basis, preserving the per-skill attribution.
- Per the upstream `CREDITS.md`: the backend, apps, and most frontend skills are
  original Zesh-One authorship; `shared/github-pr` originates from
  gentleman-programming (https://github.com/gentleman-programming) with an
  upstream license that was not confirmed at the time of the upstream release —
  it is included with explicit attribution and this caveat carried forward.
  Several frontend skills are derivative works "inspired by" gentleman-programming
  originals with substantial Zesh-One modifications.

Modifications made during vendoring
-----------------------------------
- Skill directories and their frontmatter `name:` fields were prefixed with
  their upstream domain (e.g. `security` under `backend/`, `frontend/`, and
  `dotnet-10/` became `backend-security`, `frontend-security`,
  `dotnet-10-security`). This is required because Claude Code requires unique
  skill names within a plugin, and the upstream repository organized colliding
  names under separate domain directories. No skill body content was altered.

To update: bump UPSTREAM_VERSION and re-run the vendoring against the new tag,
preserving the domain-prefix naming and the per-skill license frontmatter.
